Now I'll execute the network_fetcher tool to fetch data from the API using the default URL and parameters:

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now I'll execute the data_processing_parser tool to parse the fetched data. Since the network_fetcher output didn't include the actual data, I'll assume it was saved to the default input file as per the environment rules.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll use file_operations_reader to read the input file since the parser tool timed out. This should give me access to the data fetched by network_fetcher.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
